post_cb({"22642699": {"ViewCount": "109", "Body": "<p>Does this code do what I would expect it to do? Meaning, is the handle_(curl_easy_init()) part called before or after constructor body execution?</p>\n<pre><code>class oauth2 {\npublic:\n    oauth2() : handle_(curl_easy_init()) {\n        if (handle_ == NULL) {\n            throw new runtime_error(\"curl_easy_init return null\");\n        }\n    }\n    ~oauth2() {\n        curl_easy_cleanup(handle_);\n    }\nprivate:\n    CURL * handle_;\n};\n</code></pre>\n<p>Thanks</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "22643080", "Title": "order of constructor execution", "CreationDate": "2014-03-25T18:00:35.670", "Id": "22642699", "CommentCount": "3", "LastEditDate": "2014-03-25T18:44:37.513", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "2672165", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-25T18:44:37.513", "Score": "-1", "OwnerUserId": "781743", "Tags": "<c++><c++11>", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_22642699_22643080_4": {"length": 15, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 438}, "so_22642699_22643080_5": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 438}, "so_22642699_22643080_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.625, "section_id": 5811}, "so_22642699_22643080_2": {"length": 29, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 438}, "so_22642699_22643080_1": {"length": 6, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 438}, "so_22642699_22643080_3": {"length": 13, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 438}}, "n3337": {"so_22642699_22643080_4": {"length": 15, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 429}, "so_22642699_22643080_5": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 429}, "so_22642699_22643080_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.625, "section_id": 5584}, "so_22642699_22643080_2": {"length": 29, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 429}, "so_22642699_22643080_1": {"length": 6, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 429}, "so_22642699_22643080_3": {"length": 13, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 429}}, "n4659": {"so_22642699_22643080_4": {"length": 15, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 458}, "so_22642699_22643080_5": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 458}, "so_22642699_22643080_1": {"length": 6, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 458}, "so_22642699_22643080_3": {"length": 13, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 458}, "so_22642699_22643080_2": {"length": 29, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 458}}}, "22642768": {"Id": "22642768", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Yes.</p>\n<p>Member objects are constructed before the containing object.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-25T18:03:52.043", "CommentCount": "2", "CreationDate": "2014-03-25T18:03:52.043", "ParentId": "22642699", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "33213"}, "22643080": {"Id": "22643080", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_22642699_22643080_0\">is the handle_(curl_easy_init()) part called before or after\n  constructor body execution?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It is called before execution of the constructor body.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>C++ Standard n3337 <strong>\u00a7</strong> 12.6.2.10:</p>\n<h2>Initializing bases and members</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_22642699_22643080_1\">In a non-delegating constructor, initialization proceeds in the\n  following order: </p>\n<p id=\"so_22642699_22643080_2\">\u2014 First, and only for the constructor of the most\n  derived class (1.8), virtual base classes are initialized in the order\n  they appear on a depth-first left-to-right traversal of the directed\n  acyclic graph of base classes, where \u201cleft-to-right\u201d is the order of\n  appearance of the base classes in the derived class\n  base-specifier-list. </p>\n<p id=\"so_22642699_22643080_3\">\u2014 Then, direct base classes are initialized in\n  declaration order as they appear in the base-specifier-list\n  (regardless of the order of the mem-initializers). </p>\n<p id=\"so_22642699_22643080_4\">\u2014 <strong>Then, non-static\n  data members are initialized</strong> in the order they were declared in the\n  class definition (again regardless of the order of the\n  mem-initializers). </p>\n<p id=\"so_22642699_22643080_5\">\u2014 Finally, the compound-statement of the\n  constructor body is executed.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The <em>delegating constructor</em> in this excerpt is defined as a constructor which calls another constructor of the same class (so it delegates the job). In such a case the former is called <em>principal constructor</em> while latter is called <em>target constructor</em>. </p>\n</hr>", "LastEditorUserId": "1141471", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-25T18:30:07.083", "Score": "3", "CreationDate": "2014-03-25T18:18:14.120", "ParentId": "22642699", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "1141471", "LastEditDate": "2014-03-25T18:30:07.083"}});